ce:section.ce:para:
Investigation of the electrochemical behavior and stepwise fabrication of the aptasensor was carried out by electrochemical impedance spectroscopy (EIS). Nyquist plots of stepwise prepared electrodes were recorded by monitoring a redox couple of [Fe(CN)6]3−/4− as the probe (Fig. 3
                        ). In comparison to bare GCE (curve a), CQDs-WS2/GCE displayed sharply reduced electron transfer resistance (Ret
                        ) and approximate line Nyquist plot (curve b), demonstrating that CQDs-WS2 nanocomposites modified on bare GCE greatly accelerated the electron transfer of [Fe(CN)6]3−/4−. It is proved CQDs-WS2 nanocomposites can enhance the electron-transfer ability and enlarge effective electrode surface due to synergistic effect between electroactive WS2 and high conductive CQDs. After anchoring of aptamers on CQDs-WS2/GCE, the obvious increase of Ret
                         implied that the aptamer was successfully immobilized on the electrode surface (curve c). Because of the electrostatic repulsion, the negatively charged aptamer can restrict the access of electrons to the transducer surface, resulting in the low efficiency of electron transfer. Subsequent coating of MCH further augmented the electron transfer resistance because steric hindrance effect suppressed the interfacial electron transfer (curve d). After the aptasensor was incubated with SMZ, bigger electrochemical impedance can be detected due to the forming of aptamer-SMZ complexes which further blocked the electron transfer of electrochemical probes on GCE interface (curve e). The above EIS results not only demonstrated that as-prepared CQDs-WS2 nanocomposites have better electronic conductivity, but also indicated successful fabrication of aptasensor.
